=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;=
;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:150%;text-al=
ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;"><strong>How mu=
ch do you think Dana Walden=E2=80=99s friendship with Kamala Harris hurts o=
r helps her chances of
becoming the next C.E.O. of Disney?</strong><strong><br/></strong><strong><=
br/></strong>Well, it certainly doesn=E2=80=99t help! The Disney TV chief=
=E2=80=99s 30-year personal relationship with the former presidential candi=
date is now a liability=E2=80=94the question is <em>how much</em>. After al=
l, Disney has been running like a scared mouse from any possible confrontat=
ion with <strong>Donald Trump</strong> or his state-sponsored retribution a=
pparatus. In less than two months of Trump 2.0, the company has paid a $15
million presidential bribe=E2=80=94sorry, <em>legal settlement</em>=E2=80=
=94to make Trump=E2=80=99s ABC News suit go away; <em>de-transed</em> a tra=
nsgender character in a Disney+ show; revised corporate D.E.I. commitments;=
 and it just scaled back <em>Snow White</em> premieres to avoid media quest=
ions about the stars=E2=80=99 culture war stuff=E2=80=94which, of course, i=
s generating <em>more</em> headlines about the culture war stuff. (I=E2=80=
=99m just gonna guess that between dropping verbal bombs on her own movie a=
nd whining publicly about
not being invited to the 2022 Oscars, <strong>Rachel Zegler</strong> is pro=
bably not high on Disney casting wishlists.)<br/><br/>Anyway, if Kamala had=
 won the election, I think we=E2=80=99d be looking at Dana (and her connect=
ion to power) a lot differently. Then again, few would have thought such a =
crucial business decision as choosing the next leader of a $175 billion Ame=
rican company would be at risk of becoming so politicized. Given how the Wa=
lden-Harris friendship became an issue during the campaign,
and given how freely Trump seems to be punishing his perceived enemies, Dis=
ney=E2=80=99s board is right to worry about potential retribution and brand=
 damage if Walden is indeed chosen.<br/><br/>Of course, the political and e=
conomic climate could all change in the nine months before early 2026, when=
 Disney has said it will name <strong>Bob Iger</strong>=E2=80=99s successor=
=2E If the current financial trends con=
tinue and the country enters a Trump-c=
ession, maybe being on the president=E2=80=99s enemies list will be seen as
an asset. Ultimately, I think board chair <strong>James Gorman</strong> and=
 his succession committee will go with the candidate they believe will best=
 steer the company well beyond the Trump years. If that is ultimately Walde=
n=E2=80=94a big <em>if</em> for many reasons more legitimate than a friends=
hip with a politician=E2=80=94I think she gets the nod on the merits, regar=
dless of the short-term political problems. Still, Trump is clearly a major=
 concern, and Walden takes a hit because of
that.<br/><br/><strong>What=E2=80=99s going on with Jon Hamm on </strong><s=
trong><em>Landman</em></strong><strong>? No spoilers, but now that the show=
 was renewed, is he staying or leaving?</strong><strong><br/></strong><stro=
ng><br/></strong>Hamm only signed a one-season deal for <em>Landman</em>, a=
nd creator <strong>Taylor Sheridan</strong>=E2=80=99s plan was always for <=
strong>Demi Moore</strong>, who plays Hamm=E2=80=99s wife and was barely in=
 season one of the Paramount+ hit, to become a main character in season two=
=2E
Sheridan definitely lucked out when Moore became a hot commodity thanks to =
her awards season run for <em>The Substance</em>, just as Sheridan=E2=80=99=
s <em>Lioness</em> should get a bump from <strong>Zoe Salda=C3=B1a </strong=
>winning the Oscar for <em>Emilia P=C3=A9rez</em>. But I=E2=80=99m told <em=
>Landman</em> is also adding <strong>Sam Elliott</strong> as a main charact=
er for season two. His scenes with <strong>Billy Bob Thornton</strong> shou=
ld be fun. And Hamm, among the hardest-working men in showbiz for a few
years now, has his own show, <em>Your Friends and Neighbors</em>, debuting =
April 11 on Apple TV+.<br/><br/>As for the rest of the Sheridan-verse, he=
=E2=80=99s planning to shoot the <em>Yellowstone</em> spinoff with <strong>=
Cole Hauser</strong> and <strong>Kelly Reilly</strong> this summer (they=E2=
=80=99re currently looking to cast a <strong>Kevin Costner</strong> type th=
at is definitely <em>not</em> Costner to join them). Plus, another spinoff =
is coming together. Plus, new seasons of the existing shows, and
Sheridan is writing <em>yet more</em> original stuff. I=E2=80=99ve said thi=
s many times, but the Sheridan TV factory is pretty incredible.<br/><br/><s=
trong>Now that a Chinese film has made $2 billion, do you think there=E2=80=
=99s any chance we=E2=80=99ll soon see global blockbusters not made by Holl=
ywood?</strong><strong><br/></strong><strong><br/></strong>It seems inevita=
ble at some point, given how accessible the tools of production and distrib=
ution have become. China spent a decade learning from Hollywood how to make
their own blockbuster films, and now they don=E2=80=99t really need us. But=
=E2=80=A6 while <em>Ne Zha 2</em> has grossed an amazing $2 billion, only a=
bout $30 million of that came from outside China (and $20 million of <em>th=
at</em> was from the U.S.). We=E2=80=99ve still never seen a Chinese film (=
or a film from anywhere <em>except</em> America) gross $1 billion outside i=
ts home country, not adjusting for inflation. <em>Crouching Tiger, Hidden D=
ragon</em> is still the only Chinese movie to gross more than $100 million
in the U.S., and that was 25 years ago (and <strong>Ang Lee</strong>, the d=
irector, is from Taiwan). The big Chinese movies tend to be nationalistic o=
r rooted in local folklore. So no, I don=E2=80=99t think it=E2=80=99s happe=
ning anytime soon.<br/><br/><strong>Paramount-Skydance: Give us your update=
d odds on the merger actually happening.</strong><strong><br/></strong><str=
ong><br/></strong>I=E2=80=99d still say 80 percent to 90 percent. The Trump=
 nonsense, especially from F.C.C. chair <strong>Brendan Carr</strong> over =
the
<em>60 Minutes</em> lawsuit and =E2=80=9Cbias=E2=80=9D issues, has been lou=
d, and it could drag on and on until either the <strong>Ellisons</strong> o=
r <strong>Shari Redstone</strong> gives up. But ultimately, I still think t=
hat=E2=80=99s all just noise. The eleventh-hour bidder, Project Rise, is ki=
nd of a joke. The China issue, via investor Tencent, seems pretty minor. An=
d just today, the New York City pension funds that had argued the deal impr=
operly favored Redstone agreed to drop their effort to enjoin the merger
from closing. <strong>Larry Ellison</strong> wants this deal, and Ellison c=
arries a lot of influence with Trump. I think it=E2=80=99s as simple as tha=
t.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
